,Recommended,226100,31608604,Posted: 7 May,all,ShinjiRarenai,"I haven't played this game since it was in Early Access. I heard about this game when it was first annouced as PixelJunk, Inc. I have played PixelJunk's other games on the PlayStation platforms - PixelJunk Monsters was my favorite. I bought this game early, based on their previous work. I played for this game for a little bit, but never really got hooked. I loved their distinctive art style, but didn't really have much fun.Updates came and went, but I didn't go back to the game.Fast forward a couple of years. The game has been released, and patched several times. While looking at Factorio and Rimworld, I remembered that I had this game already. Loaded it up, and started a few levels. This game is a lot of fun!It is like a lot of other crafting/base-building games. Crashland on a planet, start building a base. Mine resources for money to expand your base. Use the native flora and fauna to make soup, and then launch the soup in a rocket to feed the hungry citizens of the galaxy!There is a more compelling gameplay loop now. You're trying to make soup faster than an off-screen rival company and put them out of business. Add more soup machines to make different flavors of soup. Variety increases market share. Add more rockets to ship the finished product faster. Start growing more ingredients to make sure your supply chain is feeding all your machines enough raw materials. Automate your production with robot workers and conveyor belts to shuttle around ingredients and soup cannisters.As your market share increases, the rival corporation will send coporate raiders - literally. You will need to create base defenses so the aliens don't come and destroy all your hard work.Instead of being thrown in the deep end with endless menus of tools, the game gives bite-sized chunks so you can learn and perfect your infrastructure. The ""aha!"" moments from getting conveyor belts and robots right is really rewarding.At first, I thought that restarting my base from scratch was annoying. However, I quickly realized that there were more efficient layouts. A base layout that might work on one planet may not work on another. Building a soup empire from grasses and vegetables will be very different than building a base from mushrooms and underground creeper vines. Killer tomatoes make great soup, but you'll need to create a herd of them that will sustain your soup production without overwhelming and kiling you.There is also a sandbox mode if you want to just keep adding on to the same base. I am still progressing through the levels, so I haven't started a sandbox-mode planet yet."
