,Recommended,226100,16049503,"Posted: 28 May, 2015",all,Note,"(My previous review of this was pretty meh. Here's to starting over.)Nom Nom Galaxy is an interesting take on all of the Minecraft/Terraria-like game. Instead of a seemingly endless adventure or quest to do, you instead complete several levels making soup, unlocking new things along the way. Your goal is to basically create enough soup to beat your opponent, all the while upgrading your soup production and protecting your base with robots.Each planet seems to have a certain generation to it instead of randomly generated levels, which I found a tiny bit disappointing. It'd be cool if the landscape and ingredients changed up, even if it was a side level away from the story mode. That aside, there are still tons of planets to go to, some even including restrictions like low-gravity or not being allowed to create extra soup rockets to send soup, so that makes up for the lack of randomization.The controls are okay but can feel a bit awkward sometimes, especially with mouse + keyboard, but it won't take too long to get used to them. With that said, it's probably better to use a controller for this game. Sometimes everything can feel a bit floaty but it's not too much of an issue.I've also seemed to notice a few strange glitches while playing which aren't too awful but are glitches nonetheless. Sometimes the game may crash when on the main hub area or you might ping off somewhere else since you were in the way of something getting built. Stuff like that.Overall, this game's a fun change from all the sandbox games coming out. I'd probably watch a few videos to see how everything works before getting it. To be honest, I'm a fan of Pixel Junk (and Q-Games in general) and bought the game since it looked cool to me. Either way, Nom Nom Galaxy's awesome."
