76561197988152187,Recommended,226100,17396110,"Posted: 5 August, 2015",all,DeepSea Spaceman,"I enjoyed what time I've spent with Nom Nom Galaxy, I've always had a weakness for building bases and making sure I have a decent supply of resources and this plays into that wonderfully.There's a bit of experimentation required to figure out how some of the features work but that's part of the charm of being a culinary pioneer eploring new worlds of flavour.There's a little bit of tower defence, a little automation and base planning, a bunch of exploring. I heartily recomend it."
,Recommended,226100,17356822,"Posted: 2 August, 2015",all,YellowReggae,"An interesting and fun game that will please any fan of the PixelJunk series. The visuals, sound and mechanics are all awesome - as per expectation. The lack of full tutorial since the last update is a bit of a problem, but once you pick up the robot-automation mechanics yourself and start using them, the game becomes a very exciting experience.My biggest issue, all that said, is that there doesn't seem to be a relationship between the scarcity of the resources and their value. Sometimes the easiest to create recipes yield the greatest payoff, which leads to you going through the same motions level after level, relying on high paid recipes rather than being more imaginative.It doesn't quite feel like the game achieves the gameplay it intends to generate. It's like 80% of the way there, which is sad as it is unlikely to have many gameplay-related changes now that the PS4 version has been released. I hope that the game is successful enough to justify a sequel as I love the potential game here, but as it stands, it leaves me feeling a little unsatisfied. Still - a definite recommendation purely based on its uniqueness and style."
